\section{The ARM \plan C compiler: [[5c]]}

% gonna present 5c (aka kencc), from Ken Thompson! simple (well not so simple).
% a nice bonus also is that it has some very nice lint checks
% e.g. dataflow 'variable set but not used'.

% some cons though to use 5c: no CFG, no IL ... very imperative ... harder case
% to defend than for the other software (5a, 5l, kernel, rio)
% but has good linting at least :) used/set warnings :)

% has integrated assembler in some sense. But actually
% LLVM does that too, see http://blog.llvm.org/2010/04/intro-to-llvm-mc-project.html

% now use for RISC-V too! richard miller's slides?

%claude:
I will explain in this book the code of the \plan ARM C compiler
[[5c]], written by Ken Thompson, which contains about 15\,000 lines
of C (plus a Yacc grammar for parsing).
%
[[5c]] is written in C, with its parser using Yacc~\cite{yacc}.
%
Like for most books in \principia, I chose a \plan program because
those programs are simple, small, elegant, open source, and
they form together a coherent set.

%claude:
[[5c]] is unusual among C compilers: it has no intermediate
representation, no control-flow graph, and no SSA form. Instead,
it works by a series of tree transformations on the AST, generating
assembly instructions directly. This makes it harder to optimize
aggressively, but also makes it remarkably easy to follow---each
phase is a straightforward tree walk.
%
A nice bonus is that [[5c]] includes lint-like checks
(e.g., ``variable set but not used'') that catch common mistakes
at compile time.

%claude:
[[5c]] is also historically significant: its design was carried
forward into the Go compiler, which was originally written in C
and derived directly from the \plan compiler sources before
being rewritten in Go in 2015. So studying [[5c]] is also,
in a sense, studying the ancestor of the Go toolchain.

\section{Other compilers}

Here are a few compilers that I considered for this book, but
which I ultimately discarded:

\begin{itemize}

%history:
%claude:
\item Dennis Ritchie's original C compiler [[cc]] (1973) was the
first C compiler, written for the PDP-11. It was a two-pass compiler
with a recursive descent parser. The code is historically
fascinating but tied to a now-obsolete architecture and
hard to follow without PDP-11 knowledge.

%history:
%claude:
\item The Portable C Compiler [[pcc]]~\cite{pcc} (1979), written by
Steve Johnson, made C portable across architectures and was used
in \unix V7 and BSD. At about 7\,000 LOC, it is a reasonable
size, but its code-generation tables are dense and hard to read.
[[pcc]] was the standard \unix compiler until GCC replaced it.

\item gcc --- about 15\,000\,000 LOC across all frontends
and backends. Even the C frontend alone is enormous. GCC
is an engineering marvel but far too large to read cover to cover.
%big. Lots of input languages. Lots of output targets.

\item clang/LLVM --- cleaner than GCC and with excellent error messages,
but the LLVM infrastructure alone is several million LOC.
The modular architecture is admirable, but the sheer size
puts it out of reach for a book like this.
