compilers small enough to read in full.

%claude:
I think [[5c]] represents the best compromise for this book:
it is a real, production compiler---used to build an entire
operating system---yet its 15\,000 LOC are within reach
of a single reader. It uses standard tools (Yacc for parsing),
targets a clean RISC architecture (ARM), and its one-pass
design, while limiting optimization, makes the code flow
easy to follow from input to output.

\section{Getting started}

% need to use 5l? not like gcc where can create executable directly
% because it calls ld under the hood. But here Unix spirit! one thing only!

To play with [[5c]], you will first need to install
the \plan fork used in \principia (see \urlinstall).

%claude:
Unlike [[gcc]], which invokes the assembler and linker
automatically, [[5c]] only compiles---you must call the
linker [[5l]] separately to produce an executable:
\begin{verbatim}
$ 5c hello.c
$ 5l hello.5
$ 5.out
Hello World
\end{verbatim}
%
You can also use [[5c -S]] to see the assembly output
without generating an object file, which is useful for
understanding what the compiler does.

%claude:
The \plan toolchain ([[5a]], [[5l]], [[5c]]) can also be compiled
natively on Linux, macOS, or Windows through
Goken9cc\furl{https://github.com/aryx/goken9cc}, so you
can cross-compile ARM programs from your regular machine.

