\section{Compiling [[helloworld.c]]}

% show ARM assembly output for a simple program.

% (at least put an arithmetic expression? "hello world, 42 is the answer!")

%claude:
Here is a minimal C program that exercises an arithmetic expression
and a [[print]] call:
\begin{verbatim}
  void main(void) {
      print("the answer is %d\n", 40 + 2);
  }
\end{verbatim}
%
Compiling it with [[5c -S]] produces assembly that shows
the three translations from the Overview: frameization
(the function prologue/epilogue), linearization (the constant
[[42]] loaded into a register and pushed as an argument),
and labelization (no branches here, just a straight-line sequence):
\begin{verbatim}
  TEXT main+0(SB), $0
    MOVW $42, R0
    MOVW R0, 4(SP)
    MOVW $s+0(SB), R0
    MOVW R0, 0(SP)
    BL   print+0(SB)
    RET

  GLOBL s+0(SB), $20
  DATA  s+0(SB)/4, $"the "
  DATA  s+4(SB)/4, $"answ"
  DATA  s+8(SB)/4, $"er i"
  DATA  s+12(SB)/4, $"s %d"
  DATA  s+16(SB)/2, $"\n\z"
\end{verbatim}
%
The constant expression [[40 + 2]]
is folded at compile time into [[42]].
The string literal [["the answer is %d\n"]] becomes a static
data item labeled [[s]], declared with [[GLOBL]] (which reserves
20 bytes) and initialized in 4-byte chunks by a series of [[DATA]]
directives.

%yoann: say again that need read assembler book to understand output
%claude:
See the \book{Assembler} for a full explanation of the [[TEXT]],
[[GLOBL]], and [[DATA]] pseudo-instructions and the addressing
modes used here ([[SB]], [[SP]], [[FP]]).

